description: A group of four young white-tailed deer spotted in the backyard. Two of them had recently been wounded, with gaping lacerations on the legs and shoulders, but they moved normally and the wounds seemed to be healing a few days later.
I believe that the bird on the right may be a Willet, while the one on the left is perhaps a Marbled Godwit.

Unsure what type of bee these guys are. Found them when I sawed through some sugar pine; they were hibernating in holes they had bored into the wood. Looked a bit like honeybees, but have no signs of striping on the abdomen, which was smooth and shiny. No discernable stinger. The first one's wings were sawed off, poor guy. Still very sluggish after several days and clearly not in their productive season.
A Willet walking and feeding with a group of Marbled Godwits.

description:
I was simply trying to clean my back patio when I realized there was a lot of orange dust on my Japanese Eggplant and my Aloe Vera. Then as I was about to remove the dust I realized there was a lot of spiderwebs. Upon further inspection, I noticed the dust moved! That’s when I realized it was a clump if baby spiders that were crawling around everywhere!!! 

I didn’t take them off yet because although I feel like they are a plague for my plants I don’t know the proper way to remove them without damaging the ecosystem (further than it already is). 

I am very interested in finding out what critter has decided my plants were the best breeding ground for its offspring.
